<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{@Vta{{}}tokorode}}}} expresses the idea of "even if". 
The past tense here is a counterfactual marker. 
In all cases, whatever is expressed in the @HI{{@EM{{@Vta{{}}tokorode}}}} clause has yet to occur.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{@Vta{{}}tokorode}}}} expresses the idea of "even if".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{don'nani@FG{{@KJ{{lower}}:hiku}}ku@FG{{@KJ{{see^volume}}:mitsu}}moxtsu@EM{{tatokorode}},@FG{{@KJ{{craft^expense}}:kouhi}}ha@FG{{@KJ{{five^hundred*million^circle}}:gookuen}}wo@FG{{@KJ{{surpass}}:ko}}erudarou.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    No matter how low we estimate the construction expense, it will go beyond 500 million yen.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{tokorode}} always follows @Vta{{}} even though its tense is not necessarily in the past and depends on the tense
of the verb in the main clause.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{east^capital}}ha@KJ{{snow}}ga@KJ{{descend}}tta@EM{{tokorode}},sonnani@KJ{{volume}}morukotohaarimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Even though it snows in Tokyo, it never snows that much.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{tokorode}} is used between two contrasting clauses to emphasise that something is less than expected or that the outcome
stated in the first clause will be unfavourable.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{now}}kara@KJ{{busy}}ide@KJ{{going}}tta@EM{{tokorode}},1@KJ{{time}}no@KJ{{new^tree*trunk^line}}niha
    @KJ{{interval}}ni@KJ{{fit}}imasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    No matter how much we hurry now, we're not going to be in time for the one o'clock Shinkansen.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{@Vta{{}}tokorode}}}} can only be used where there is a clear counterfactual meaning and where the main clause is either explicitly or implicitly negative.
<a href="grammar-te-mo.html">@HI{{@Vte{{}}mo}}</a> can always replace @HI{{@EM{{@Vta{{}}tokorode}}}}; however, since @HI{{@Vte{{}}mo}} can be used to express something factual and can be used with a positive
main clause, there are cases where @HI{{@Vte{{}}mo}} cannot be replaced with @HI{{@EM{{@Vta{{}}tokorode}}}}.
</p>

<p>
Note that this usage is completely different to the usage of <a href="">@HI{{tokorode}}</a> as a device to change topic.
</p>

<p>
Note also that <a href="grammar-tokoro.html#complete">@Vta{{}}@HI{{tokoro}}</a> without the @HI{{de}} has a different meaning.
</p>

